         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in order to ... <hi>Sanskrit</hi> • near to ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> • yellow (obl.pl.m.)  </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> • for the sight </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the beasts of the forest  </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">for the sake of <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">with absence of danger • <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> from the sheath • <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">he kept desiring <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> • quickly-quickly </seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">This small fragment belongs to a leaf of the same manuscript to which <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns12and516"/> belongs. The text contains Tocharian B translations of words and phrases, first of the Mahāvadānasūtra (in the lines a1 to a4), and second from the Śrāmaṇyaphalasūtra (in the lines a5 to b5). Some of them have parallels in Tocharian A, namely <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a460"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a466"/>, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a461"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a465"/>.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="lingcomment">Since <hi>luwo</hi>, pl. <hi>lwāsa</hi> is genus alternans the expected for of the adjective would be pl. f. <hi>wärttoṣṣana</hi> instead of pl. m. <hi>wärttoṣṣeṃ</hi>. It is either a mistake or more likely the use of the verse form that was used in literary language. The source text has Skt. <hi>mṛghabhūta-</hi> 'savage beast'.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">This line corresponds to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a460"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a466"/> a4.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">This line corresponds to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a460"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a466"/> b2.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">This line corresponds to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a460"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a466"/> b3.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">This line corresponds to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a461"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a465"/> a1.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment">The form <hi>rämermer</hi> is the result of the <hi>āmreḍita</hi>-compound <hi>rämer-rämer</hi>. Following the regular accentuation the form <hi>rämér-rmer</hi> underwent regular geminate simplification.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">This line corresponds to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a461"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a465"/> a2.</note></p>
         </div>
